      • updateDisplay

        public static void updateDisplay()
        Update Display Routine.

        Display must be updated whenever the value of currentDriver is changed. In general this is done by calling the updateDisplay routine. In certain cases (e.g. begin sub-block, enter normal procedure) this is simply a matter of adding a new level and is done by inline coding. In other cases (e.g. exit from a sub-block, connection block, prefixed block) the current level is simply deleted and therefore no action is necessary at all.

      • BB

        public static void BB(Prototype pp)
        This routine is used to initiate a sub-block instance. Its main functions are:

        • Create driver for sub-block. Insert static link 'drp' and various booleans.

        • Create object and link it to the sub-block driver.

        • Attach the sub-block driver to its dynamic environment.

        • Update current driver pointer and insert a new level in display.

        • Enter the sub-block's declaration code.

        Parameters:
        pp -

      • detach

        public void detach()
        The detach procedure implemented is an extension of that defined in common base language. Detach need not be in the outer block of a class or prefixed block. We scan the dynamic chain 'drex' starting from current driver until we find an instance of a class or prefixed block. This instance is then detached according to common base and given a reactivation point which points to the statement following the detach.

        There are two cases:

        • Object not detached:

          The return point 'pex' and and dynamic link 'drex' are retrieved from the driver of the object. These are replaced in the driver by a complete reactivation point whose 'pex' points to the statement after the detach statement and whose 'drex' points to the driver in whose block detach was called. If detach was called in the outer block of the class, 'drex' points to the objects own driver. Control is now passed to the point after the class generation, the accumulator stack being restored if necessary.

        • Object detached already:

          A complete reactivation point is stored in the driver of the object. The prefixed block which represents the QPS of which the object is a component is located by following dynamic links (and static links when a detached object is encountered). The outer sequence control of the QPS must be set to indicate the prefixed block itself as the currently operating component. This is done by following dynamic links back from the driver of the prefixed block until the driver of a detached object (in an outer QPS) is found. This driver is given an incomplete reactivation point which points tothe driver of the prefixed block. Finally, the prefixed block itself is resumed by taking its reactivation point from its driver. If this is an incomplete reactivation point, we follow 'drex' pointers to locate a driver containing a complete reactivation point ('pex' not null). This is then the driver of the subblock, procedure etc. in which the prefixed block was previously suspended.

      • call

        public RTObject call(RTObject obj)
        Call causes the active phase of a QPS component to be used as a procedure. The reactivation point of the component being called is retrieved. 'pex','drex' of the detached object at the head of the component become a normal return point leading to the point at which the component was called. The detached bit is cleared and the components which is now attached begins to operate at its earlier reactivation point.

        Parameters:
        obj - The object to be Called (Coroutine)
        Returns:
        The object to be Called

      • resume

        public RTObject resume(RTObject obj)
        Resume is performed in three principal stages:

        • A reactivation point is set for the currently operating component. this is done by searching 'drex' links from current driver until the driver of the detached object at the head of the component is located. A complete reactivation point is set.

        • The reactivation point for the component to be resumed is retrieved. This is done by beginning with the master driver of the object referenced and following 'drex' pointers until a complete reactivation point is found. This gives the new current driver and program address.

        • Set the outer sequence control of the QPS containing the resumed component. We locate the prefixed block of the QPS containing the component to be resumed. We follow 'drex' pointers from this until we find the driver of nearest detached object. An incomplete reactivation point pointing to the component to be resumed is set in this driver.

        Parameters:
        obj - The object to be Resumed
        Returns:
        The object to be Resumed
